////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
// Acid Test: Unnecessary Declarations
//
// A Rule or Theorem may not begin with a Let declaration, because its free
// variables are already implicitly universal.  This used to crash validation
// with an uncaught error from processRules.  Now the leading Let is flagged
// 'unnecessary' during interpretation and:
//
//   - validation ignores it as if it were deleted (it contributes nothing to
//     the propositional form, is never a Weeny, does not assign ProperNames
//     to its scope, and is disregarded by isBadInstantiation), so the Rule
//     still means the universal closure the author presumably intended - and
//     if the Let has a body, the copy of the body remains as a given, giving
//     the typed universal closure;
//   - the Let receives an 'inapplicable' validation result with reason
//     'unnecessary declaration' (the ⊘ marker in Lode and the web UI - the
//     same marker used for syntax the CAS does not support) and a scoping
//     error { unnecessary: [...] } (the web UI hover message, combined with
//     any redeclaration error on the same Let).
//
// Each section below uses its own disjoint constants so that rules and
// instantiations cannot cross-justify between sections.

➤ "a Rule may not start with a Let: flagged, but still usable universally"
{
  Declare P, c
  Rule: :{ Let x ⊘  P(x) }
  P(c) ✔︎
}

➤ "a Rule may not start with a typed Let: flagged, typed universal closure"
{
  Declare N, Q, d
  Rule: :{ Let y be such that N(y) ⊘  Q(y) }
  Assume N(d)
  Q(d) ✔︎
}

➤ "a Theorem may not start with a Let: flagged, its Rule copy still usable"
{
  Declare R, e
  Theorem: { Let z ⊘  R(z) }
  R(e) ✔︎
}

➤ "a leading Let that also redeclares gets both errors"
{
  Declare S
  Let w
  Rule: :{ Let w ⊘  S(w) }
}
